# RaFood API – Project Context

## Stack

- **Python** 3.10, **Poetry** for dependencies
- **FastAPI** for the API
- **SQLModel** + **SQLAlchemy** (async) for ORM
- **Alembic** for migrations
- **PostgreSQL** (async via asyncpg)
- **pytest** + **pytest-asyncio** for tests
- **structlog** for logging
- **Prometheus** + **Grafana** for monitoring
- **Ruff** for linting/formatting, **mypy** for type checking
- **pre-commit** for hooks; **Locust** for load tests

## Project structure

- `src/` – application code (domains under `src/<domain>/`)
- `tests/` – `tests/unit/` (service tests with mocks), `tests/feature/` (API tests with real DB)
- `docs/adr/` – Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)
- `alembic/` – migrations (`alembic/versions/` for revision files)
- `locust/` – load test definitions
- `kubernetes/`, `grafana/`, `prometheus/` – deployment and monitoring

## Domain contexts (from ER / README)

- Restaurants (and restaurant schedules)
- Products
- Offers (and offer schedules)
- Categories
- Users

## API wiring

- Routers are registered in `src/api.py` with `include_router(..., prefix='/<resource>', tags=[...])`.
- App uses prefix from settings: `APP_V1_PREFIX` (e.g. `/api/v1`). Full base path for API routes: `/api/v1/<resource>`.
- Main app: `src/main.py` (middleware, exception handlers, router mount).

## ADRs

- ADRs live in `docs/adr/`; naming: `XXX-short-description.md`.
- Create new: `make create-adr name='short-descriptive-name'`.
- Important ADRs: 001 (services/repositories), 002 (error handling), 004 (hexagonal), 006 (logging), etc.

## Commands – Makefile is the source of truth

All project commands are in the **Makefile** (run `make help` for the full list). Use it as the single reference.

**When you generate new code**, run quality checks **automatically** (format, lint, type check, tests) to ensure the code is good. See the quality-checks rule. Fix any failures.

**You must never:**

- Run **migrations** or anything that changes DB or deployment state: no `make migrate`, `make rollback`, `make create-migration`, `make start`, `make stop`, `make build`, etc.
- Touch **git**: no `git add`, `git commit`, `git push`, `git checkout`, or any git command. Do not make any permanent change to version control.
- Run any command that alters the environment, deploys, or persists data (e.g. no `poetry install` unless the user explicitly asks).

The only commands you run are quality checks (format, lint, type check, test), and only when you have generated or changed code—automatically, to guarantee the code is good.

## Response language

Prefer **English** for agent responses. **Portuguese (pt-BR)** is also acceptable—reply in pt-BR when the user writes in Portuguese, or in English when they write in English. Code, identifiers, and technical terms stay in English.
